                            <div class="padding-left-40 margin-top-20">
                                4-5 mn reading
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="padding-left-40 padding-right-40">
                    {# INTRO #}
                    <div class="c-learn-article-page__introduction">
                        Experimentation requires an Entrepreneurial spirit. It is
                        an attitude that embraces critical questioning, followed
                        by quick actions and continuous improvements…
                    </div>
                    <img src="{{ asset('/images/learn/experimentation/experiment-funnel.png') }}" alt="" class="c-learn-article-page__image">
                    {# WHY #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">Why?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        {# <span class="bold">Incubation is learning about the product market fit.</span> It is necessary to capture
                        the recipe for success before full scale to ensure sustainable revenue. It is about
                        finding the most effective route to market to reach early adopters. It’s about unlocking business impact, testing and learning on disruptive activations and fine-
                        tuning a market positioning. <br/>
                        <br/>
                        <span class="medium">
                            Remember that every time you bring a new innovation to market, you are
                            adding one more SKU in the market place so your argument must be a strong one.
                        </span> #}
                        <span class="bold">Experimenting is a way to lower the risk on investing in a NEW idea</span> (products
                        or services) by testing & learning at an early stage with consumers to understand
                        traction. Making tests happening in a in a small realistic environment (a city or
                        even a district in a city) should enable you to collect learnings and unlock
                        consumer value. <br/>
                        <br/>

                        <span class="medium">An idea has no/little value until tested against reality.</span> It’s only when you know
                        you are onto something, that you can invest a bigger amount of capital.
                    </p>
                    <img src="{{ asset('/images/learn/experimentation/experiment-why.png') }}" alt="" class="c-learn-article-page__image">
                    {# WHAT #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">What?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        <span class="bold">Plan some tests according to what you need to learn</span> on consumer traction
                        while consuming the fewest time & resources. It’s about making sure you ask the
                        right questions to understand where value comes from with your early adopters
                        before launch. <br/><br/>

                        If you wonder <span class="bold">"Is there a consumer need worth solving?" with no offer ready
                        yet</span>, you can learn from consumers with no final offer yet by doing Interviews in
                        bars, shops, private parties, landing observations… collecting insights on pain
                        points, using digital interaction to address in an agile way positioning, naming,
                        design… <br/><br/>

                        If you wonder <span class="bold">"Have I built something that solves that need in a specific
                        market?" build for Experimental Editions</span>, it’s all about minimum viable product
                        or services to put fast on the field to test consumer desirability. For product,
                        micro production capabilities (internally or with 3rd partner) are required. For
                        service, it is all about developing minimum required features to capture usage.
                    </p>
                    {# HOW #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">How?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        <span class="bold">Build partnerships to get access to consumers and capture evidences</span> from
                        the field in a restricted environment targeting early adopters (limited numbers of
                        hotels, bars, restaurants, shops, private parties…).  <span class="medium">Learn fast on the field with
                        customers, consumers</span>… requires having a structured approach:
                    </p>
                    <img src="{{ asset('/images/learn/experimentation/experiment-how.png') }}" alt="" class="c-learn-article-page__image">
                    <ul class="c-learn-article-page__list">
                        <li>Identifying <span class="bold">hypotheses</span> on where value comes from</li>
                        <li>Getting a point of view on <span class="bold">criteria of success</span>, thresholds</li>
                        <li>Setting <span class="bold">metrics</span>, KPIs both quantitative and qualitative, parameters to capture evidence</li>
                        <li>Collecting <span class="bold">feedbacks</span> and key facts and figures with people on the field</li>
                    </ul>
                    {# WHEN #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">When?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        <span class="bold">Before Capex investment</span> it’s shall be done in a lean way to allow iteration at a
                        small cost. It requires people on the field to capture evidences and sponsors to
                        facilitate decision making.
                    </p>
                    {# TIMING #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">Timing?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        <span class="bold">Speed in the validated learning</span> (test & learn feedback loop: build, measure,
                        learn) means you do something right! It shall last in between 3 weeks and 3 months
                        on incremental ideas and up to 6 months on breakthrough ideas.
                    </p>
                    {# CHALLENGES #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">Challenges</h2>
                    <div class="c-learn-article-page__quote">
                        <div class="title">
                            <span class="quote-left"></span>
                            <span>
                                No amount of experimentation can prove <br>
                                me right; one experiment can prove me <br>
                                wrong.
                            </span>
                            <span class="quote-right"></span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="subtitle">Albert Einstein</div>
                    </div>
                    {# QUESTIONS #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">Questions to have in mind</h2>
                     <ul class="c-learn-article-page__list">
                        <li>What activities do I need to do to learn about consumer traction?</li>
                        <li>What is the lowest investment I can do to learn it?</li>
                        <li>How long should be my test?</li>
                        <li>Where should I test it?</li>
                        <li>What current PR structure can help me?</li>
                        <li>Do I need external partners?</li>
                        <li>What information do I need to track?</li>
                        <li>What criteria shall I put in place for my dashboard?</li>
                        <li>When should I iterate my original idea?</li>
                        <li>Do I review the progress on a regular basis to make decisions and move forward?</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
